POSTGRESQL

    This session introduces the relational model and explains how ACID properties ensure data consistency in PostgreSQL.
    Participants will learn the various data types available in PostgreSQL and how to choose the right type for each column.
    We will explore constraints such as primary key, foreign key, unique, and check to enforce data integrity.
    The concept of normalization from 1NF to 3NF will be explained with practical table design examples.
    Different types of joins like inner, left, right, and full joins will be practiced with real queries.
    Subqueries and Common Table Expressions (CTE) will be used to simplify complex SQL logic.
    Indexing techniques using B-tree and hash indexes will be demonstrated for query optimization.
    Transactions and isolation levels will be covered to understand concurrency handling.
    Creation of views and materialized views will be used to simplify reporting queries.
    Triggers and PL/pgSQL functions will be introduced for automating database actions.
    The EXPLAIN ANALYZE tool will be used to understand query performance.
    Table partitioning strategies will be discussed for handling large datasets.
    JSONB support in PostgreSQL will be used for semi-structured data.
    UPSERT operations using ON CONFLICT will be implemented.
    Roles and permission management will be covered for security.
    Backup and restore strategies will be demonstrated.



MONGODB

    The session explains how the document model differs from relational tables.
    BSON structure and how MongoDB stores data internally will be discussed.
    Basic CRUD operations will be practiced using Mongo shell.
    The difference between embedded and referenced documents will be taught.
    Aggregation pipeline will be used for analytics queries.
    Indexing strategies in MongoDB will be explored.
    Full-text search capabilities will be implemented.
    Schema versioning techniques will be introduced.
    Pagination using skip and limit will be practiced.
    Lookup operations will be used as join alternatives.
    Multi-document transactions will be demonstrated.
    Validation rules will be added to collections.
    Change streams will be used for real-time events.
    Basics of sharding and scalability will be explained.
    MongoDB Atlas cloud features will be explored.
    Common performance pitfalls will be discussed.



REDIS

    Redis key-value mindset will be introduced.
    String operations will be used for counters and caching.
    List data type will be applied for queues.
    Set operations will be used for unique collections.
    Hashes will store structured user sessions.
    Sorted sets will be used for leaderboards.
    TTL feature will be applied for expiring data.
    Pub/Sub model will be used for messaging.
    Streams will be introduced for event logs.
    RDB and AOF persistence models will be compared.
    Cache-aside and write-through patterns will be explained.
    Rate limiting logic will be built using Redis.
    Distributed locks will be implemented.
    Redis as session store will be demonstrated.
    Monitoring and debugging Redis will be practiced.



NEO4J

    Graph database concepts will be introduced.
    Nodes and relationships will be created.
    Cypher query language basics will be practiced.
    Pattern matching in graphs will be explored.
    Graph traversal techniques will be implemented.
    Shortest path algorithms will be demonstrated.
    Indexing in Neo4j will be configured.
    Recommendation logic will be built.
    Graph data modeling will be discussed.
    CSV import into Neo4j will be shown.
    Performance tuning for graphs will be explained.
    Community detection concepts will be introduced.
    Centrality measures will be calculated.
    Access control in Neo4j will be covered.
    Real-world graph use cases will be discussed.


INFLUXDB 

    Time-series database concepts will be introduced.
    Measurements and points structure will be explained.
    Difference between tags and fields will be taught.
    Retention policies will be configured.
    Basic Influx queries will be practiced.
    Continuous queries will be created.
    Down-sampling strategies will be implemented.
    Telegraf agent setup will be shown.
    Alerting mechanisms will be designed.
    Kapacitor basics will be introduced.
    Dashboard concepts will be discussed.
    Write performance tuning will be explained.
    Schema design for metrics will be taught.
    Monitoring use cases will be implemented.
    Integration with applications will be demonstrated.



